<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Create Creature Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        How to spawn rare creature-type enemies such as Gargoyles, Bane, and Baalrogs.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What Create Creature Does
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Create Creature</Bold> Event Point is used to spawn creature-style enemies rather
        than ordinary human NPCs. These are rare compared with normal enemies and civilians, so it is
        best to keep them isolated in a clear colour and letter group.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        For example, you might use <Bold>Group A</Bold> and <Bold>Colour Red</Bold> for creature
        Event Points. This is not required, but it makes the mission easier to inspect later because
        creature spawns stand out from police, civilians, ordinary enemies, counters, messages, and
        objective logic.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_creature_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Recommended grouping:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Because creatures are uncommon, keep them in an obvious isolated group, such as Group A / Red.
                    This is only a convention; you can use any colour and letter group you prefer.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Adding a Creature
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To add a creature spawn, click <Bold>Add</Bold> in the Event Points panel, choose
        <Bold>Create Creature</Bold>, and click <Bold>OK</Bold>. This opens the
        <Bold>Edit EventPoint</Bold> window with creature-specific properties.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_creature_add_type.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph>
        As with other Event Points, first set the common properties. Choose a letter group and
        colour, then place the creature on the map.
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select a clear letter group, such as <Bold>A</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select a clear colour, such as <Bold>Red</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>Select Position on Map</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click the desired spawn position in the viewport.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_creature_common_properties.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Creature Type and Count
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The creature-specific section lets you choose the creature type and the number to spawn.
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Bat</Bold> — appears in the list, but may not work correctly in the release version.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Gargoyle</Bold> — a working release-version creature option.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Bane</Bold> — the electrified Bane creature from the end-level style encounter.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Baalrog</Bold> — the large fire ape-style creature.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,8,0,0">
        In the release version, the practical working options appear to be <Bold>Gargoyle</Bold>,
        <Bold>Bane</Bold>, and <Bold>Baalrog</Bold>. <Bold>Bat</Bold> appears in the list but should
        be treated as uncertain unless tested in game.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_creature_type_count.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Count
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Count</Bold> field is editable, but testing suggests that only one creature spawns
        per Event Point regardless of the number entered. If you want multiple creatures, create
        multiple Create Creature Event Points instead of relying on Count.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#3A2A2A" BorderBrush="#7A4A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0A0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Important:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Count appears to be available in the editor, but in practice only one creature appears to spawn per Event Point.
                    Use separate Event Points for multiple creatures.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Trigger Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To make the creature appear as soon as the mission starts, use the standard immediate
        trigger setup:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Triggered By:</Bold> None / Game Starts.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Listening Mode:</Bold> Active.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_creature_trigger_settings.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Rotating the Creature Facing Direction
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Event Points have a facing direction. When an Event Point is selected, an orange bulb or
        handle appears at the top of the marker. You can click and drag this handle to rotate the
        Event Point in place.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        For example, after placing two Baalrogs, select each one and rotate the orange handle so the
        creature faces toward Darci’s Player Event Point.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_creature_rotate_facing.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>
